{"title_page": "Cromdale (clipper)", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=ital}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = File:Cromdale (ship, 1891) - SLV H91.325-1436.jpg\n| Ship caption = The Cromdale\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header              =\n| Ship country              = United Kingdom\n| Ship flag                 = {{shipboxflag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n| Ship name                = ''Cromdale''\n| Ship owner               =  \n| Ship ordered             = \n| Ship builder             = [[Barclay Curle]], [[Glasgow]]\n| Ship original cost       = \n| Ship laid down           = \n| Ship launched            = June, 1891\n| Ship acquired            = \n| Ship commissioned        = \n| Ship decommissioned      = \n| Ship in service          = \n| Ship out of service      = \n| Ship renamed             = \n| Ship struck              = \n| Ship reinstated          = \n| Ship honours             = \n| Ship captured            = \n| Ship fate                = Wrecked in 1913\n| Ship status              = \n| Ship notes               = \n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Cromdale''''' was the last [[clipper]] ship built for the Australian [[Wool|wool trade]].  \n\n==Background==\nThe American clipper ship era lasted from 1845 until 1860, shortly before the [[American Civil War]] broke out. Meanwhile, British clippers continued to be built into the 1870s before they were shifted into the wool trade. The opening of the [[Suez Canal]] in 1869 was the eventual demise of the tea clipper as the shorter route allowed larger cargo ships passage to China.<ref name=\"Skrabec\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IBYJbFS52f0C&pg=PA44&dq=Australian+wool+trade+clipper&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiq2vKG8L7jAhVIJt8KHR6YAwkQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Australian%20wool%20trade%20clipper&f=false|title=The 100 Most Significant Events in American Business: An Encyclopedia|author=Quentin R. Skrabec|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2012|page=45|accessdate=July 18, 2019}}</ref> The remaining clippers profited by serving the wool trade as the need for coal hindered steamships from reaching Australian ports. The shift eventually came when steamships became so large that they could hold an ample amount of coal without constantly refueling.<ref name=\"Skrabec\"/> By the time of ''Cromdale''{{'}}s launch in 1891, [[ocean liner]]s that could carry large amounts of passengers and cargo had entered the scene.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Cromdale (ship, 1891) - SLV H99.220-4076.jpg|left|thumb|200px|The wreck of the Cromdale]]\n''Cromdale'' was built at [[Barclay Curle]] in [[Glasgow]], and launched in June, 1891. She had an identical sister ship named ''Mount Stewart'' that was launched a month earlier from the shipyard.<ref name=\"RMG1\">{{cite web |title=Merchant Shipping: Agreements, Crew Lists And Official Logs: CROMDALE & MOUNT STEWART |url=https://collections.rmg.co.uk/archive/objects/560852.html |website=Royal Museums Greenwich |publisher=Royal Museums Greenwich |accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref> These ships had the most modern features of their time in terms of structure and design. The first master of ''Cromdale'' was a captain named E.H. Andrew, who was very experienced and up to date on the newest technological features.<ref name=\"Colonial Clippers\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/colonialclippers00lubbrich|quote=Clipper cromdale.|title=The Colonial Clippers|author=[[Basil Lubbock]]|publisher=J. Brown & son|year=1921|page=[https://archive.org/details/colonialclippers00lubbrich/page/335 335]& 336|accessdate=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe was ultimately lost in 1913 under the command of ''Captain Arthur'' while she was homeward bound from [[Taltal]] with a cargo of [[nitrate]]. ''Cromdale'' was 126 days out heading for [[Falmouth, Cornwall|Falmouth]] (UK) and had been in dense fog for a few days. While a steamer passed and advised Arthur to alter his course, a light was suddenly seen ahead through the fog shortly afterwards. Arthur tried to turn the ship about but it was too late, and she struck rocks at the foot of a cliff. This cliff was discovered later to be part of [[Bass Point (England)|Bass Point]] which is close to [[Lizard Lighthouse]].<ref name=\"RMG\">{{cite web |title=Merchant Shipping: Agreements, Crew Lists And Official Logs: MOUNT STEWART. |url=https://collections.rmg.co.uk/archive/objects/560854.html |website=Royal Museums Greenwich |publisher=Royal Museums Greenwich |accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref> The lifeboats were ordered lowered immediately due to the damage the ship had endured, but luck was on the side of the crew. The weather was calm, distress rockets were at hand, and rescuers from land arrived shortly to assist. ''Cromdale'' was declared a total loss after she settled quickly, and was found to be laying in a position that was exposed to the elements.<ref name=\"Colonial Clippers\"/>\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat-inline|Cromdale (ship, 1891)}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Clipper ships}}\n{{coord missing|Atlantic Ocean}}\n\n[[Category:Clippers]]\n[[Category:Individual sailing vessels]]\n[[Category:Victorian-era merchant ships of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1913]]\n[[Category:1891 ships]]\n[[Category:Wool trade]]\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=ital}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = File:Cromdale (ship, 1891) - SLV H91.325-1436.jpg\n| Ship caption = The Cromdale\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header              =\n| Ship country              = United Kingdom\n| Ship flag                 = {{shipboxflag|United Kingdom|civil}}\n| Ship name                = ''Cromdale''\n| Ship owner               =  \n| Ship ordered             = \n| Ship builder             = [[Barclay Curle]], [[Glasgow]]\n| Ship original cost       = \n| Ship laid down           = \n| Ship launched            = June, 1891\n| Ship acquired            = \n| Ship commissioned        = \n| Ship decommissioned      = \n| Ship in service          = \n| Ship out of service      = \n| Ship renamed             = \n| Ship struck              = \n| Ship reinstated          = \n| Ship honours             = \n| Ship captured            = \n| Ship fate                = Wrecked in 1913\n| Ship status              = \n| Ship notes               = \n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Cromdale''''' was the last [[clipper]] ship built for the Australian [[Wool|wool trade]].  \n\n==Background==\nThe American clipper ship era lasted from 1845 until 1860, shortly before the [[American Civil War]] broke out. Meanwhile, British clippers continued to be built into the 1870s before they were shifted into the wool trade. The opening of the [[Suez Canal]] in 1869 was the eventual demise of the tea clipper as the shorter route allowed larger cargo ships passage to China.<ref name=\"Skrabec\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IBYJbFS52f0C&pg=PA44&dq=Australian+wool+trade+clipper&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiq2vKG8L7jAhVIJt8KHR6YAwkQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Australian%20wool%20trade%20clipper&f=false|title=The 100 Most Significant Events in American Business: An Encyclopedia|author=Quentin R. Skrabec|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2012|page=45|accessdate=July 18, 2019}}</ref> The remaining clippers profited by serving the wool trade as the need for coal hindered steamships from reaching Australian ports. The shift eventually came when steamships became so large that they could hold an ample amount of coal without constantly refueling.<ref name=\"Skrabec\"/> By the time of Cromdale's launch in 1891, [[ocean liner]]s that could carry large amounts of passengers and cargo had entered the scene.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Cromdale (ship, 1891) - SLV H99.220-4076.jpg|left|thumb|200px|The wreck of the Cromdale]]\n''Cromdale'' was built at [[Barclay Curle]] in [[Glasgow]], and launched in June, 1891. She had an identical sister ship named ''Mount Stewart'' that was launched a month earlier from the shipyard.<ref name=\"RMG1\">{{cite web |title=Merchant Shipping: Agreements, Crew Lists And Official Logs: CROMDALE & MOUNT STEWART |url=https://collections.rmg.co.uk/archive/objects/560852.html |website=Royal Museums Greenwich |publisher=Royal Museums Greenwich |accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref> These ships had the most modern features of their time in terms of structure and design. The first master of ''Cromdale'' was a captain named E.H. Andrew, who was very experienced and up to date on the newest technological features.<ref name=\"Colonial Clippers\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/colonialclippers00lubbrich|quote=Clipper cromdale.|title=The Colonial Clippers|author=[[Basil Lubbock]]|publisher=J. Brown & son|year=1921|page=[https://archive.org/details/colonialclippers00lubbrich/page/335 335]& 336|accessdate=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe was ultimately lost in 1913 under the command of ''Captain Arthur'' while she was homeward bound from [[Taltal]] with a cargo of [[nitrate]]. ''Cromdale'' was 126 days out heading for [[Falmouth, Cornwall|Falmouth]] (UK) and had been in dense fog for a few days. While a steamer passed and advised Arthur to alter his course, a light was suddenly seen ahead through the fog shortly afterwards. Arthur tried to turn the ship about but it was too late, and she struck rocks at the foot of a cliff. This cliff was discovered later to be part of [[Bass Point (England)|Bass Point]] which is close to [[Lizard Lighthouse]].<ref name=\"RMG\">{{cite web |title=Merchant Shipping: Agreements, Crew Lists And Official Logs: MOUNT STEWART. |url=https://collections.rmg.co.uk/archive/objects/560854.html |website=Royal Museums Greenwich |publisher=Royal Museums Greenwich |accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref> The lifeboats were ordered lowered immediately due to the damage the ship had endured, but luck was on the side of the crew. The weather was calm, distress rockets were at hand, and rescuers from land arrived shortly to assist. ''Cromdale'' was declared a total loss after she settled quickly, and was found to be laying in a position that was exposed to the elements.<ref name=\"Colonial Clippers\"/>\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat-inline|Cromdale (ship, 1891)}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Clipper ships}}\n{{coord missing|Atlantic Ocean}}\n\n[[Category:Clippers]]\n[[Category:Individual sailing vessels]]\n[[Category:Victorian-era merchant ships of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 1913]]\n[[Category:1891 ships]]\n[[Category:Wool trade]]\n", "name_user": "Gatoclass", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground:format", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cromdale_(clipper)"}
